HEADWORD: Almude
<hw>Al*mude"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg.
<ets>almude</ets>, or Sp. <ets>almud</ets>, a measure of grain or dry
fruit, fr. Ar. <ets>al-mudd</ets> a dry measure.]</ety> <def>A measure
for liquids in several countries. In Portugal the Lisbon almude is about
4.4, and the Oporto almude about 6.6, gallons U. S. measure. In Turkey
the ⟦ldquo⟧almud⟦rdquo⟧ is about 1.4 gallons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

